// Package apiserver provides the machinery for building Kubernetes-style API servers.
// It is a generic library for building aggregated API servers that integrate with
// the Kubernetes API aggregation layer.
//
// # Overview
//
// The apiserver library contains reusable components to create API servers that can
// be aggregated with the main Kubernetes API server. Extension API servers built with
// this library automatically get features like:
//   - Delegated authentication and authorization
//   - kubectl-compatible discovery information
//   - Admission control chains
//   - Versioned API types
//   - OpenAPI schema generation
//
// # Extension API Servers and API Aggregation
//
// Extension API servers are separate processes that serve custom APIs and register
// themselves with the main Kubernetes API server via API aggregation. The aggregation
// layer proxies requests for custom API groups to the appropriate extension server.
//
// Extension servers register with the aggregation layer by creating APIService objects
// that specify which API groups and versions they handle. This allows custom APIs to
// appear seamlessly alongside core Kubernetes APIs.
//
// # Preferred Alternatives
//
// For most use cases, Custom Resource Definitions (CRDs) and admission webhooks are
// preferred over building full extension API servers:
//
//   - CRDs: Declarative way to extend the Kubernetes API without writing server code.
//     Use CRDs when you need CRUD operations for custom resources with standard Kubernetes
//     storage semantics.
//
//   - Admission Webhooks: Mutating and validating admission webhooks allow customizing
//     request processing without building a separate server. Use webhooks for validation,
//     defaulting, and policy enforcement.
//
// Build an extension API server only when you need capabilities that CRDs and webhooks
// cannot provide, such as custom storage backends, protocol translation, or aggregation
// of external systems.
//
// # Key Packages
//
// The library is organized into several major sub-packages:
//
// # pkg/server
//
// The server package contains GenericAPIServer, the core building block for API servers.
// GenericAPIServer handles:
//   - HTTP request routing and serving
//   - TLS configuration
//   - Graceful shutdown
//   - Health checking (healthz, readyz, livez)
//   - OpenAPI spec generation and serving
//   - Post-start and pre-shutdown hooks
//
// RecommendedConfig and RecommendedOptions provide pre-configured defaults suitable
// for most extension servers.
//
// # pkg/admission
//
// The admission package provides the admission control framework. Admission controllers
// intercept requests before objects are persisted and can:
//   - Mutate objects (MutationInterface)
//   - Validate objects (ValidationInterface)
//   - Reject requests
//
// Key interfaces include Interface, MutationInterface, and ValidationInterface.
//
// # pkg/authentication
//
// The authentication package handles request authentication. It provides:
//   - authenticator.Request interface for authenticating HTTP requests
//   - authenticator.Token interface for token-based authentication
//   - User information extraction and propagation
//
// Extension servers typically delegate authentication to the main API server.
//
// # pkg/authorization
//
// The authorization package handles request authorization. The authorizer.Authorizer
// interface determines whether authenticated users can perform requested actions.
// It supports decisions: Allow, Deny, and NoOpinion.
//
// Extension servers typically delegate authorization to the main API server.
//
// # pkg/endpoints
//
// The endpoints package constructs REST endpoints from storage implementations.
// APIInstaller converts registry.Store implementations into HTTP handlers with:
//   - Standard REST verbs (GET, LIST, WATCH, CREATE, UPDATE, PATCH, DELETE)
//   - Subresource handling
//   - Content negotiation
//   - Metrics and tracing integration
//
// # pkg/registry
//
// The registry package provides the storage layer abstraction:
//   - rest.Storage: Base interface for RESTful storage
//   - rest.StandardStorage: Full CRUD operations
//   - generic.Store: Implementation backed by etcd or other storage
//   - RESTCreateStrategy, RESTUpdateStrategy, RESTDeleteStrategy: Strategy interfaces
//     for customizing object lifecycle behavior
//
// # pkg/server/options
//
// The options package provides reusable configuration options for servers including:
//   - RecommendedOptions: Pre-configured options bundle for extension servers
//   - SecureServingOptions: TLS and HTTPS configuration
//   - EtcdOptions: Storage backend configuration
//   - Authentication and authorization delegation options
//
// # GenericAPIServer
//
// GenericAPIServer is the heart of any extension API server. It provides:
//   - HTTP/HTTPS serving with configurable TLS
//   - Request handling pipeline (authentication, authorization, admission)
//   - API group installation via InstallAPIGroup and InstallLegacyAPIGroup
//   - Discovery endpoint generation
//   - Graceful shutdown with configurable timeout
//   - Integration with the Kubernetes lifecycle (post-start hooks, readiness)
//
// To build an extension server:
//  1. Create a RecommendedConfig from RecommendedOptions
//  2. Build a GenericAPIServer using config.Complete().New()
//  3. Create APIGroupInfo structures for your API groups
//  4. Install groups via server.InstallAPIGroup()
//  5. Run the server via server.PrepareRun().Run()
package apiserver

